          German teams are typically less adventurous than French sidea, but Julian N. Has Hoffenheim firing these days, and the fact they are at home means this will certainly be a tough game for City. I want to wait for lineups to be released to predict the game 100%, but I know if Sane and Sterling start on the wings it will spell problems for Hoffenheim. Their pace and the ability to switch play and generate goals from the opposite channel of the build up is uncanny, and its something an aggressive team like Hoffenheim will struggle with if they press hard. And if they dont press I cant see them generating goals on the counter attack, simply because thats not what this squad is built for. If City bring the big guns on the wings they will win 3 or 4 to 1 id guess. If they dont both play Im leaning more towards 2-1 or 2-2. And that could be 2-1 hoffenheim!

        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          It isn't really in Julian Nagelsmann's nature to play for a draw but that would be the prudent thing to do. This is their toughest home CL fixture by a country mile (Lyon have been mercurial away from the Parc OL over the last couple of seasons and Donetsk are usually underwhelming save for a few notable results) and going all-out for a win represents too much of a risk for me after picking up a point away to Donetsk & City losing at home at Lyon. Hoffenheim were done on the counter against Leipzig and although that is a problem for all possession teams, it makes little sense trying to play a typical 'home' game against the best possession-football team, and manager, in Europe. A high press has worked against Pep in the past but give his teams space to counter attack into and they can tear you apart. I fancy Hoffenheim to get some joy down City's left on the counter and City to get some joy down Hoffenheim's. For the spectacle, I would like a shootout. City have more guns. 1-3.
